content: On August 29, 1993, the Atlanta Braves achieved a significant milestone by clinching their first National League West title in Atlanta after moving from the city of Milwaukee. The Braves defeated the San Diego Padres 5-3 at Fulton County Stadium, led by a strong performance from pitcher Tom Glavine, who went eight innings and struck out ten batters. This victory marked the beginning of a dominant era for the Braves, culminating in their run to the World Series that season.
